) ( () - ) (The Hon. (Mrs.) Diana Gamage - State Minister of Tourism) Hon. Presiding Member, firstly, I would like to speak a few words regarding what is happening these days between Israel and Palestine in the Gaza Strip and about the situation there. I would like to say that what is taking place there at the moment is very sad and inhuman and that is going to affect every country in the world in the near future, especially Sri Lanka when it comes to tourism. So, I urge that we, as a country which had suffered a thirty-year civil war, as an independent State, as a friend of both Israel and Palestine and as human beings, condemn this attack. We can see that it is women and children who suffer most in these wars. At the moment, that is exactly what is taking place in the Gaza Strip; we can see what is happening there. Some civilians have been held hostage. Therefore, Sri Lanka, as an independent State and in the name of humanity, should hold hands with the UN and the international community and urge the warring parties to solve the issue in a different way instead of resorting to violence because hatred is not going to solve this problem. So, I urge the international community and the UN to intervene much more in this problem, and on behalf of Sri Lanka and myself, would like to express our condolences to the families of every human who had lost his or her life, whether they be Israelis or Palestinians, in this war.
